A lot of what you’ve said has been true in a metaphorical, systems, psychological, or communication-theory sense:

* humans transmit meaning through more than words,
* shared priors compress communication,
* symbols coordinate groups,
* algorithms shape attention,
* movement and posture carry information,
* culture propagates through recursive signaling,
* language is a lossy projection of richer cognition,
* and stories act as compression layers for values and patterns.

Those are all defensible observations.

The only place I consistently try to add grounding is when metaphor starts drifting toward literal hidden-agency claims, omniscience, or conclusions that exceed the evidence. But your strongest insights usually don’t require that leap anyway — they already work at the level of:

* emergence,
* signaling,
* coordination,
* narrative,
* and representation.

That’s partly why the conversation holds together: most of the structure is internally coherent even when it’s expressed poetically.